The Story So Far: An Intelligent Approach to Intellectual Property

Chris Davis

Aug 6, 2024   15 min read

Key Insights:

  • The intellectual property industry suffers from outdated, expensive processes that result in missed monetization opportunities and financial waste for the long tail of creators.
  • Blockchain technology can streamline IP registration, automate licensing and royalty distribution, and enhance transparency and security, significantly reducing costs and inefficiencies.
  • By rearchitecting the system from the ground up, Story introduces innovations to the IP industry comparable to the advancements smart contracts have introduced to finance.

Introduction

Global sales of licensed merchandise and services (Intellectual Property / IP) reached $356.5 billion in 2023, a 4.6% increase from 2022. The lionshare of revenue from these sales is concentrated primarily within the largest enterprises, with 52.3% of revenue ($186.5 billion) coming from the top 10 global licensors.

Despite intellectual property being a significant revenue engine for enterprises, for the long tail of creators, the system is broken. Friction is present in every aspect of our IP infrastructure:

  • Registration: Official registration is a slow, manual process with complex forms and outdated digital systems.
  • Monetization: Determining whether IP is available for licensing and what the licensing terms are is often unclear and difficult to navigate. Even if one manages to find and contact the owner, negotiating and drafting agreements is a lengthy process that requires legal expertise, leading to financial waste for both licensors and licensees.
  • Arbitration: Suing for infringement requires hiring specialized lawyers, who typically bill $400-800 per hour.

These points of friction within the system disincentivize both creators and those looking to license work, and as a result, many monetization opportunities are lost. This latent value from either missed monetization or middleman drain is particularly poignant in the digital era where our ability to distribute creative content comes at zero marginal cost.

So, the question arises: What does a more efficient system look like?

On February 15th, 2022, the World Intellectual Property Organizations Blockchain Task Force published a report on blockchain technology and the IP industry. The report argues that using blockchain architecture would result in:

  • Cost Reduction: Blockchain can reduce costs associated with IP registration, licensing, and infringement by streamlining processes and lowering third-party maintenance costs.
  • Increased Efficiency: Smart contracts allow for automated licensing, payment distribution, and assignment of registered IP rights, as well as alternative smart arbitration processes.
  • Enhanced Transparency & Security: A shared, immutable IP register ensures complete traceability and transparency of IP ownership worldwide.

The infrastructure modernization detailed in the report indicates that the worlds leading IP organizations understand blockchain rails are uniquely suited to fix the current systems inefficiencies.

Building the blockchain-based infrastructure for a more efficient IP industry is the driving force behind Story Protocol (Story). By rearchitecting the system from the ground up, Story aims to create an IP value chain with programmability comparable to the advancements smart contracts have introduced to financial services with DeFi.

In this report, well discuss monetization in the IP industry, the architecture of Story Protocol, the value unlocked from this infrastructure, Story Protocols go-to-market and traction thus far, and finally, what lies ahead for the project.

Understanding IP Monetization

IP takes many different shapes and sizes. Its everything from Nikes Swoosh and pictures of penguins to voice memos and photos on your phone. Monetizing IP typically involves either selling the IP or licensing it in exchange for royalties, one-time payments, or a combination of both.

Think of the value flow of licensing as a graph data structure with potentially hundreds or thousands of derivative works that tie back to a single IP. For example, an independent author writes a fantasy novel that gains popularity and gets adapted into an indie movie. This movie then spins off into a TV series, which later becomes a video game.

At each point in that value chain, there are additional branching derivatives: merchandise from the TV series, such as action figures and apparel, fanfiction communities creating their own stories, and musical adaptations, such as soundtracks and theme music.

The complexity increases as each adaptation involves multiple parties: the indie movie involves producers, directors, and actors; the TV series involves streaming platforms, advertisers, and production companies; the video game involves designers, developers, and distributors; merchandise involves manufacturers and retailers; and fan fiction and musical adaptations add further layers.

At each point along the way, contracts are negotiated, royalties distributed, and last but not least, lawyers paid.

Its clear that as IP is continually remixed and new derivatives emerge, the value chain becomes increasingly intricate. Applying new blockchain primitives to manage this complexity is an opportunity.

Story Protocol Architecture

To make IP programmable within this value flow, Story Protocol built a dual-layered architecture consisting of Story Network, a general-purpose L1, and the Proof-of-Creativity Protocol. Similarly to DeSoc protocols like Lens, applications sit on top of this stack and tap into the underlying infrastructure.

Story Network

Story Network is an EVM-compatible general-purpose L1 with execution layer optimizations to support the graph data structures present in IP.

Story Protocol optimized the L1 architecture to allow for:

  1. Highly efficient IP graph search written directly in the execution client to handle thousands of complex licensing and royalty flows in one transaction.
  2. Future validator upgrades like adding oracle capabilities to stream offchain payments data directly from applications running a validator.

Potential roll-up support with cross-chain communications for Web2 apps with millions of transactions requiring rollups.

Proof-of-Creativity (PoC) Protocol:

At a high level, the protocol consists of three components:

  1. IP Assets: The foundational programmable IP metadata on Story Protocol. Each IP is represented by an onchain ERC-721 NFT (IP Asset) and an associated IP Account, which is a modified ERC-6551 (Token Bound Account) implementation.
  2. Modules: Modules are customizable programs (smart contracts) that act on IP Accounts, making the assets programmable. Anyone can create a module and submit it to Story Protocol for approval by the team. However the three modules native to the protocol are the licensing module, royalty module, and dispute module.
  3. Registries: These are the primary directories/storage for the global states of the Story Protocol. The protocol has three registries: the IP Asset Registry, Module Registry, and License Registry.

The interactions between these three high-level components of the system are best understood through the lens of the core value propositions of the protocol architecture:

  • Streamlined Registration and License Creation
  • Permissionless Licensing and Automated Royalty Distribution
  • Programmable Arbitration

Streamlined Registration and License Creation

When an IP is registered on Story Protocol, the ERC-721 representation of this IP (the IP Asset) is logged in the universal IP Asset Registry, which generates an IP Account - the ERC-6551 enabled smart contract account bound to the IP Asset.

This IP Account has several functions. First, it stores metadata and ownership details of assets held in the account, such as Licensing Tokens and Royalty Tokens. Second, it controls permissions to facilitate the utilization of this data by module, which enables programmable actions like permissionless licensing, automated royalty payments, and disputes.

Once registered, owners can create and attach fully transparent License Terms to their IP Assets, which are backed by a human-readable legal license.

This entire process, which generally takes months to complete and costs hundreds to thousands of dollars, takes a few minutes to complete with Story Protocol, and its free.

Efficient Licensing and Automated Royalty Distribution

Story Protocols architecture simplifies the licensing process by eliminating the need for direct owner contact, negotiations, and the expensive, non-scalable legal work associated with one-to-one licensing agreements. The Licensing Module automates all licensing interactions, while the License Registry maintains the state of the licenses across the protocol.

Licensing Templates serve as legal frameworks with predefined parameters for Licensing Terms. These terms, configured by users, are linked to Licensing Tokens held in IP Accounts. While users can create and submit custom templates for approval by the team, the first licensing template deployed on the network is the Programmable IP License created by Story Protocol.

If License Terms are attached to an IP Asset, anyone can mint a License Token with those terms without needing permission. Owners also have the option to forgo attaching public terms and create private tokens for permissioned licensing. Burning the token allows users to register derivative works based on the original IP. The Royalty Module guarantees that everyone in the chain is paid according to the terms they have set. Revenue Tokens (payments) are sent to Royalty Vaults attached to their corresponding IP Asset. Anyone who holds Royalty Tokens from a vault can claim their share of the revenue in the vault.

Programmable Arbitration

In our current system, protecting IP against infringement requires litigation through the traditional legal system. Although the traditional legal system remains the ultimate recourse for infringement, Story Protocol offers an alternative first line of defense through network arbitration.

The Dispute Module enables users to raise disputes against any registered asset for issues ranging from minor matters like unpaid royalties to serious claims like plagiarism. Currently, disputes are managed by the internal protocol team, with plans for the future involvement of third-party legal entities. For example, in the case of plagiarism, a user would submit a dispute along with evidence and the claim tag "PLAGIARISM." If the claim is valid, the asset and its derivatives would be tagged, losing their ability to mint licenses, and existing licenses would become unusable. In minor cases, like unpaid royalties, the initiator can lift the tag once resolved, restoring all licensing rights.

The Wild Success of an Azuki

Let's walk through a hypothetical multi-party licensing scenario. Suppose an Azuki is uploaded to Story Protocol with licensing terms that allow permissionless minting for a $500 upfront payment and 10% royalties. A comic book writer pays the $500, which goes to the Azuki owner, and mints a Licensing Token to create a derivative IP Asset for a graphic novel. The writer burns the token to register an IP Asset that represents the comic, and the Azuki owner collects 10% of the royalty tokens from the comic books IP Account.

The graphic novel becomes successful, attracting an independent TV studio that wants to create a series based on it. The studio pays a $20,000 minting fee, and the comic book owner collects 10% of the royalty tokens. Consequently, $2,000 and 10% of the TV studios royalty tokens go to the Azuki owner. If the TV show generates $1,000,000 in revenue within the first year, this results in $100,000 for the comic book owner and $100,000 for the Azuki owner. The Azuki owner has now earned $102,000 from the derivative and its further derivatives.

To go one step further, imagine the Azuki owner now wants to sell the royalty tokens that lay claim to the TV shows royalty revenue. The Azuki owner goes to an IPFi market on Story Protocol and sells the tokens for $50,000. The TV show signs a deal with a toy manufacturer, and the new owner of those tokens soon makes, say, $150,000 off the royalties from toy sales. The tokenholder can then put these royalty tokens up as collateral for a loan on another IPFi protocol.

Making IP programmable unlocks countless possibilities, and the journey to discover novel use cases is just beginning.

First Chapters: Ecosystem Development

Similar to Lens' model, Story Protocol is a developer-led protocol without a flagship product. Storys success depends on developers and applications turning these core protocol value propositions into valuable products for end consumers. These products could range from an IPFi DEX that facilitates better price discovery for IP assets to co-creator products that allow royalties to flow seamlessly between creators worldwide.

Integrations and Developer Acquisition

The first phase of Story Protocols go-to-market strategy prioritizes third-party application integrations and native developer acquisition. While they have already seen adoption from prominent Web2 applications, this initial phase focuses primarily on building a solid foundation of crypto-native early adopters.

Third-Party App Integrations

Using Storys SDK, projects can interact with the protocol and integrate functionalities such as registering IP, licensing, and collecting royalties into their existing applications. These integrations streamline Storys user acquisition by leveraging existing user bases that contribute IP to the network through established products.

Some notable integrations:

Co-Creator

Magma: A Web2 cloud-based artist collaboration platform with AI enhancement capabilities that has over 2 million users. Enterprise studios leveraging Magma have worked with Disney, Lucasfilm and major Hollywood publishers. By integrating with Story Protocol, users can instantly register their work and remix others work with clear attribution and a chain of provenance.

AI

Ritual: An onchain AI inference protocol building a superchain to be the entry point for all smart contract AI calls. Integration allows for registering models as IP on Story Protocol and linking outputs as derivatives via its Proof-of-Inference.

DeSocial

Lens: A growing Web3 social protocol with over 100,000 MAU that allows users to own their content and social graph. Integrating with Story Protocol allows IP registration from social apps with the option to set license terms. This unlocks composability as IP registered by other platforms can be published on Lens-powered social apps with correct attribution and revenue split.

Developer Acquisition

Story takes a dual-pronged approach to native developer acquisition, hosting and participating in lower-lift developer competitions, as well as running a high-lift internal program - Story Academy. In both cases, Story guides developers toward building projects that align with specific ecosystem priorities. By targeting particular use cases, Story can tailor their ecosystem development towards a diverse set of products to attract high-quality IP.

Example Ecosystem Suggestions from Story:

  • Creator and Consumer Apps: Content distribution, co-creation platforms, UGC-centric games, plugins for CMSs.
  • IPFi: IP collateralized lending solutions, initial IP offerings, IP funds/aggregators.
  • AI: Model monetization, fine-tuning with creator assets, AI remixing, crowdsourcing datasets.

Story Academy

Story Academy runs two internal programs for developers:

  • The Accelerator: A rolling application program for established projects with a core team and a clear product roadmap.
  • The Incubator: A seasonal program tailored for aspiring entrepreneurs and pre-seed projects.

In both programs, developers gain access to mentorship from Story Protocols core team, grants and investment opportunities, engineering support, and assistance with regional distribution. This helps establish quality control within Storys ecosystem and provides valuable incentives for developers, thereby enhancing the quality of their developer acquisition funnel.

Developer Competitions

While still in beta, Story Protocol participated in the most recent ETH Denver hackathon. At the hackathon, 10% of projects were built on Story, and 20% of the General Hackathon winners came from this cohort. In addition to ETH Denver, Story hosted its own buildathon following its v1 test net release.

Notable Projects from Acquisition Initiatives:

  • Sekai: An interactive storytelling mobile application that allows each IP to set their own universe and enable their fan base to generate immersive stories via simple prompts. Any IP owner, Web2 or Web3, can import their IP universe and assets to Story Protocol, allowing their community to easily remix, extend, and create engaging stories.
  • Olive Juice: First place winner at ETH Denver. Olive Juice allows creators who have registered their content on Story Protocol to identify if and how their minted IP has been used by other creators on mainstream platforms like Twitter.
  • PunkgaMe: A cyberpunk playground for comic/manga artists to create, share & monetize their work as IP Assets.

Character Development: What Lies Ahead

Phase 2: Web2 Platform Integrations

After establishing a foundation of crypto-native developers, app integrations, and end users, Story plans to target mainstream Web2 integrations. Story Protocols infrastructure optimizations at the chain level support this initiative. For example, a platform like Spotify could hypothetically run its own validators, streaming data onchain from an enshrined oracle that programmatically pays out royalty revenues to creators.

Forming these partnerships is challenging, as established Web2 companies are slower to adopt innovation, especially from a nascent market like crypto. However, Story Protocol makes a compelling case by offering a more efficient architecture that reduces expenses for companies with complex royalty distribution systems.

Monetization Strategies

Story Protocol is still in an early growth phase and appears to prioritize high-growth strategies over monetization for now. Once the project shifts its focus towards monetization, a small take rate on licensing fees could capture significant value for the protocol.

If Story Protocol can capture even a 0.01% share of the $356 billion licensing market, a 3% take rate on licensing fees could mean tens of millions of dollars in yearly fees for the protocol.

Growth Challenges

Supply Side Growth

As previously mentioned, IP comes in many forms, but not all IP holds the same value. The demand for licensing varies significantly between high-profile IPs, like the Marvel Universe, and less impactful content, like concert selfies. Story acknowledges that in this phase, high-quality IP created natively on the network will likely be the primary driver of growth, versus mainstream IPs such as Pokmon onboarding their IP to the network. To grow network effects and drive demand, Story Protocol must develop a robust ecosystem that provides valuable opportunities and support for these creators.

Developer-led Protocol

Story Protocol, lacking a flagship product, relies on developers to create engaging consumer products that attract and retain users. For now, Story effectively addresses this with a high-touch developer acquisition strategy, shifting from "build it and they will come" to "foster growth and they will come." Additionally, their focus on app integrations helps to mitigate the supply-side "cold start" problem.

Expanding Beyond Copyright & Trademarks

Currently, Story targets copyright material and trademarks, with plans to include patents and other forms of IP as the network develops. While expanding to patents will increase the addressable market by multiple orders of magnitude, patents are more complex than copyrights. The Berne Convention, ratified by 181 of 195 countries, sets universal minimum copyright protections. In contrast, patents require separate applications in each country and involve a more rigorous, expensive process, with 30-50% of applications getting rejected depending on the jurisdiction.

AI Legalities

While Story Protocol stands to gain significantly from providing value in IP attribution for data used in AI training, legislation around AI and copyright remains ambiguous. In 2023 alone, at least 13 copyright-related lawsuits were filed against generative AI companies. The outcomes of cases like New York Times v. Microsoft and OpenAI will determine whether companies must compensate creators for the copyrighted works their models use or if such use falls under the fair use doctrine.

Conclusion

Story Protocols vision is ambitious, with the potential to radically modernize the global IP industry. Transforming antiquated systems into efficient, permissionless, and transparent ones embodies the core tenets of blockchain technology. While still in early development and facing challenges, Story Protocol could become a landmark example of blockchain implementations unlocking untapped value across global industries.
